{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.24,0.04,0.18,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112519"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94553"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9158"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46189"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112519"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86 year old man presents to the General Surgical clinic with a large epigastric hernia that has been present for 10 years. It is easily reducible. Recently, he has been experiencing discomfort, especially during exertion. He describes the hernia as progressively growing in size. He has a medical history of mild but well-controlled chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia. He underwent a laparoscopic cholecystectomy 11 years ago. His medications are metformin, gliclazide, olmesartan and rosuvastatin. He smokes five cigarettes per day but does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has a large epigastric hernia (Images 1-2) which is easily reducible with a hernia defect size of approximately 2 cm. His current weight is 87 kg with a height of 175 cm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management of his epigastric hernia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management with no surgery","Use of a hernia belt to help manage discomfort from the epigastric hernia","Book elective open repair of the hernia with sutures","Prehabilitation with repeat clinic to facilitate surgery","Book elective open repair of the hernia with mesh"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a symptomatic epigastric hernia that ultimately requires surgical repair to improve his symptoms. However, before proceeding with any repair, the most appropriate next step is \u003Cstrong\u003Eprehabilitation\u003C/strong\u003E, which in this case would include smoking cessation, optimisation of diabetes and COPD. He is overweight and should be encouraged to lose several kilograms. This approach aims to reduce perioperative risks and improve surgical outcomes. This should be further assessed prior to booking of surgery to ensure progress has been made\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking cessation is particularly important as it can significantly reduce postoperative complications, including wound healing issues and pulmonary complications. Even a short period of preoperative smoking cessation (4-8 weeks) can lead to meaningful improvements in surgical outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptimisation of diabetes control, aiming for a good HbA1c level, is crucial to reduce the risk of surgical site infections and improve wound healing. Similarly, optimising COPD management and ensuring good lung function preoperatively can reduce the risk of postoperative pulmonary complications. These are important in reducing the risk of surgical site infection and hernia recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E without surgery is not appropriate in this case as the hernia is symptomatic and progressively enlarging. Watchful waiting is generally reserved for asymptomatic hernias or in patients who are poor surgical candidates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehernia belt\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary relief of abdominal discomfort but is not a definitive solution for a symptomatic, enlarging hernia. It could be considered as a temporising measure while the patient is being optimised for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen repair of the hernia with sutures\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not the best option for this patient. The man\u0027s hernia defect size is 2 cm, which would have a higher recurrence rate if repaired with sutures alone. Generally, hernias with defects larger than 1-2 cm require mesh repair to reduce the risk of recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen repair of the hernia with mesh\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be the ultimate surgical approach, it is not the most appropriate next step. The patient\u0027s modifiable risk factors should be addressed first to optimise surgical outcomes and reduce perioperative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while this patient will likely require surgical repair with mesh in the future, the most appropriate next step is to address his modifiable risk factors. This approach will help to ensure the best possible outcome when he does undergo surgical repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Optimisation of modifiable risk factors is crucial before elective hernia repair in patients with comorbidities.","Epigastric hernias with defects larger than 1-2 cm generally require mesh repair to reduce recurrence risk.","Smoking cessation prior to surgery can significantly reduce postoperative complications."],"references":["Turner RC. A GP primer on incisional hernia. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018 Sep;47(9):609-612. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/d08c5067-57bb-46d3-825c-ec8534e9d971/A-GP-primer-on-incisional-hernia.aspx","Augenstein VA, Colavita PD, Wormer BA, Walters AL, Bradley JF, Lincourt AE, et al. CeDAR: Carolinas Equation for Determining Associated Risks. Journal of the American College of Surgeons. 2015;221(4, Supplement 1):S65-S6. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1072751515006390"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94553"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20810"},{"type":"media","id":"20811"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20810"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/F6Rc66L1R24mIwCDyl30iEMawytXVT.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/F6Rc66L1R24mIwCDyl30iEMawytXVT.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"media","id":"20811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20811"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cWcLqDP1QqgPGaJ6ay0UsL4dRcMVyC.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cWcLqDP1QqgPGaJ6ay0UsL4dRcMVyC.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94553"},